1. Data quality¶

You will generate some data quality insights for two models we have worked in the past:

  • DFT error estimation

The first model is based on a regularized Ridge algorithm and the code is given. Use the L2 model with = 2. Also, notice that the features are already imputed with zero values when a subgroup is absent. In your analysis, you need to calculate the completeness as the percentage of non-zero elements per column.

Explore the distribution of the output error we are predicting¶

In [6]:
f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (28, 12), dpi = 100)
# Left plot: Histogram
sns.distplot(y, kde = False, norm_hist = False, rug = True, label = "Output: y", ax = axes[0])
axes[0].set_title('Distribution of DFT errors: histogram')
axes[0].set_xlabel('DFT error (kcal/mol)')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Count of observations')

# Right plot: Kernel Density Estimation
sns.kdeplot(y, shade = True, clip = (y.min(),y.max()), bw_method = 1, label = "Output: y", ax = axes[1])
axes[1].set_title('Kernel density estimation')
axes[1].set_xlabel('DFT error (kcal/mol)')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Density of observations')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Create a Ridge regression model ($L_2$ regularization)¶

In [9]:
# Smaller values, stronger regularization, more coefficients will go to zero
# You can also use: alphas = np.logspace(-2,0,10) to generate 10 logarithmically spaced points between 10^-2 and 10^0.

# Initiate the Ridge Model (L2 Logistic Regression Model)
Model_L2 = linear_model.Ridge(alpha=2)

# Fit the model
Model_L2.fit(X_train, y_train)
Train_Error_L2 = np.mean(abs(Model_L2.predict(X_train) - y_train))
Test_Error_L2  = np.mean(abs(Model_L2.predict(X_test) - y_test))
Model_Coeff_L2 = Model_L2.coef_
NonZeroCoeff_L2 = X.shape[1] - (Model_L2.coef_ == 0).sum()

print('Train error for Ridge Regression Model =', Train_Error_L2)
print('\nTest error for Ridge Regression Model =', Test_Error_L2)
print('\nRidge Regression Model Coefficients: \n', Model_Coeff_L2)
print('\nRidge Regression Model Non-0 Coefficients =', NonZeroCoeff_L2)

Compute Completeness¶

In [10]:
completeness = []
for i in range(713):
    temp = np.count_nonzero(X_train.iloc[:,i] / len(X_train.iloc[:,i]) * 100)
    completeness.append(temp)

Comment¶

From the graphs above, there seems to be no significant correlation between the feature importance and the dataset completeness, however from the log-log graph, it can be observed that after completeness crosses 4, the points hardly fall under 0 and exceed 30, also as the completeness increases, the chances of points falling under -2 are lessening.

Another observation from the semi-log graph is that most points are centered and evenly spread at 0th feature importance

Therefore I would recommend and porbably implement the redesigning of the dataset with more complete features as more completeness of features would generally have higher feature importance and would have a greater accuracy overall.
